The '''Andhra Pradesh State Department of Archaeology and Museums''' is a department of the [[Government of Andhra Pradesh]] which oversees archaeological exploration and maintenance of [[heritage sites]] and [[museums]] in the [[Indian state]] of [[Andhra Pradesh]]. It was established in the year 1914 under the stewardship of Dr. Gulam Yazdani. As a result of formation of A. P. State in 1956, the Department of Archaeology and Museums, Hyderabad was expanded and it became known as Andhra Pradesh Department of Archaeology and Museums in the year 1960.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aparchmuseums.nic.in/about.html|title=About Archaeology Department of Andhra Pradesh|date=2015|website=Andhra Pradesh Department of Archeology & Museums |accessdate=6 October 2017}}</ref> When the state of [[Telangana]] was formed in 2014<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/andhra-pradesh/2018/apr/02/vontimitta-temple-to-get-permanent-structures-in-andhra-pradesh-1795849.html|title=Vontimitta temple to get permanent structures in Andhra Pradesh|work=The New Indian Express|access-date=2018-11-16}}</ref>, the department was separated into two; leading to disputes between the two newly-formed departments over historical artifacts.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/140822/nation-current-affairs/article/tussle-over-historic-artefacts-telangana-and-andhra-pradesh |title=Tussle over historic artefacts in Telangana and Andhra Pradesh |last= |first= |date=22 August 2014 |website=[[Deccan Chronicle]] |publisher= |access-date=10 October 2017 |quote=}}</ref>
== See also == *[[Archaeological Survey of India]] *[[Amaravathi Mahachaitya]] *[[Culture of Hyderabad]]
