{{Infobox person | name = Sofía Álvarez | image = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = Sofía Stefani Espinoza Álvarez | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1989|05|05}} | birth_place = [[Coahuila]], [[México]] | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = | nationality = Mexican | party= [[Independent politician|Political independent]] | occupation = {{flat list| * Author * Advocate * Columnist * Philanthropist * Political and Social Activist }} | years_active = 2011–present | children = | alma_mater =[[Sul Ross State University]] |website = {{plainlist| {{URL|sofiaalva.com}} * {{URL|https://www.facebook.com/sofiastefanialva |Facebook}} * {{URL|https://www.instagram.com/sofiaespinozaalvarez |Instagram}} * {{URL|https://twitter.com/@sofiaealvarez |Twitter}}}} }}
'''Sofía Stefani Espinoza Álvarez''' is a Mexican-American [[author]], [[researcher]], and advocate. As a researcher and [[criminologist]], she has participated in an intensive program of research aimed at providing readers with evidence-based information and analysis of the issues of [[Latinos]] in the [[United States]].<ref name="springer.com">{{cite web|url=https://www.springer.com/new%20&%20forthcoming%20titles%20(default)/journal/41276 |title=Latino Studies |website=Springer.com |date= |accessdate=2016-12-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tsulaw.edu/news/thurgood_today_issues/TTJANUARY_2016.pdf |format=PDF |title=Thurgood Today |date=January 2016 |website=Tsulaw.edu |accessdate=2016-12-09}}</ref>
==Education== She is a law graduate from Universidad de León in [[Mexico]], and holds a Bachelor of Science degree in criminal justice from [[Sul Ross State University]] in [[Texas]], United States. Her areas of legal interest include Mexican and [[American jurisprudence]], [[philosophy of law]], [[constitutional law]], [[immigration law]], [[law and society]], and [[penology]].
==Academic career== Álvarez maintains an active professional career and research and publication agenda, publishing various academic book chapters, journal articles, and books. Her research has been published in national and international peer-reviewed journals, including "Capital Punishment on Trial: Who Lives, Who Dies, Who Decides—A Question of Justice?" (''Criminal Law Bulletin'', 2014); and "Neoliberalism, Criminal Justice, and Latinos: The Contours of Neoliberal Economic Thought and Policy on Criminalization" (''Latino Studies'', 2016). Her books include, ''Immigration and the Law: Race, Citizenship, and Social Control Over Time'' (forthcoming); ''Ethnicity and Criminal Justice in the Era of Mass Incarceration: A Critical Reader on the Latino Experience'' (2017); and ''Latino Police Officers in the United States: An Examination of Emerging Trends and Issues'' (2015).<ref name="springer.com"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=c6N5CgAAQBAJ&pg=PR5&lpg=PR5&dq=sofia%20espinoza%20alvarez&source=bl&ots=Z5gjCvn0PO&sig=myVy0Ktb-7Kef_jem4IkajjOy1c&hl=es&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwih4PWoq-HQAhVEQiYKHdxxA8U4ChDoAQgzMAY#v=onepage&q=sofia%20espinoza%20alvarez&f=false|title=TWENTY-FIRST CENTURY DYNAMICS OF MULTICULTURALISM: Beyond Post-Racial America|first=Martin Guevara|last=Urbina|date=19 September 2014|publisher=Charles C Thomas Publisher|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://srinfo.sulross.edu/cv/files/urbina_martin_murbina.pdf |format=PDF |title=Martin Guevara Urbina, PhD : CV |website=Srinfo.sulross.edu |accessdate=2016-12-09}}</ref>
==Activism and philanthropy== In addition to her work as a legal scholar and academic endeavors in research, publication, and social activism, Álvarez assists people with immigration-related issues, including visa requirements, judicial and legal translations, and procedures for obtaining different types of visas for legal residence. Conjointly, Álvarez endeavors as a columnist at [[Univision]] and [[Huffington Post]] where she portrays her research on the ethnic realities of Latinos and the U.S. legal system, and illustrates the importance of key issues, such as representation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.univision.com/temas/sofia-espinoza-alvarez|title=Sofía Espinoza Álvarez: Últimas noticias, videos y fotos de Sofía Espinoza Álvarez - Univision|website=Univision.com|accessdate=2016-12-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/author/sof%C3%ADa-espinoza-%C3%A1lvarez|title=Sofía Espinoza Álvarez|publisher=[[The Huffington Post]]|accessdate=2016-12-09}}</ref>
Vested in positive social transformation, since 2013, Álvarez has been working with migrants traveling to the U.S. through Mexico, seeing first-hand the global dynamics of immigration, and thus prompting her to start a non-profit organization, the Empower Global Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sofiaalva.com/actividadessociales/|title=Actividades Sociales/Fundaciónes|date=14 April 2016|website=Sofiaalva.com|accessdate=2016-12-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://fundacionjaff.mx/en/about-us/contact/ |title=Fundación Jaff &#124; Contact |website=Fundacionjaff.mx |date= |accessdate=2016-12-09}}</ref>
==Political participation== Álvarez has been a part of pro-society and pro-migrant associations, such as Operation Monarca. She was an organizer of the human wall that took place along the US-Mexico border in February 2017 in solidarity with the migrants.<ref>http://www.excelsior.com.mx/nacional/2017/02/17/1147014</ref>
Being involved in social movements and not being a militant of any political party, she was invited by the movement pro-independent candidates in Mexico, to work as state coordinator of the Movimiento Ola 365, for local and federal Mexican elections of 2018. Ola 365's central objective is to position 365 independent candidates, in an attempt to "refresh" the Mexican political system. <ref>http://despertarmexico.com/ola365-la-resistencia-antisistema/</ref>
==Works or publications== *''[https://books.google.com.mx/books/about/Uispanics_in_the_U_s_Criminal_Justice_Sy.html?id=8A5nswEACAAJ&redir_esc=y Hispanics in the U.S. Criminal Justice System: Ethnicity, Ideology, and Social Control]'', with [[Martin Guevara Urbina]] (2018). {{ISBN|978-0398092160}} *[https://g.co/kgs/81Ly6M''Immigration and the Law: Race, Citizenship, and Social Control,''] with [[Martin Guevara Urbina]] (2018). {{ISBN|978-0-816-537624}}.<ref name="Google Books">{{cite web|url=https://g.co/kgs/81Ly6M= |title=Google Books: Authors |website= Google.com |date= |accessdate=2017-11-09}}</ref> *''[https://books.google.com.mx/books?id=f8A3DgAAQBAJ&dq=ethnicity+and+criminal+justice+mass&source=gbs_navlinks_s Ethnicity and Criminal Justice in the Era of Mass Incarceration: A Critical Reader on the Latino Experience]'', with [[Martin Guevara Urbina]] (2017). {{ISBN|978-0398091538}} * [https://books.google.com/books?id=eVavCAAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1&hl=es&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Latino Police Officers in the United States: An Examination of Emerging Trends and Issues''] (2015). {{ISBN|978-0-398-08144-7}}.<ref name="ccthomas.com">{{cite web|url=https://www.ccthomas.com/booksby.cfm?A_Lname=Alvarez&A_Fname=Sofia%20Espinoza&A_ttl= |title=Charles C Thomas Publisher: Authors |website=Ccthomas.com |date= |accessdate=2016-12-09}}</ref>
